  "prompt": "Are there specific laws targeting money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, many countries have specific anti-money laundering (AML) laws and regulations. In the United States, key laws include:\n\n1. Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Requires financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Mandates record-keeping and reporting requirements\n\n2. Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Criminalized money laundering as a federal offense\n- Established penalties for individuals and organizations\n\n3. USA PATRIOT Act\n- Enhanced AML regulations after 9/11\n- Increased reporting and monitoring requirements\n- Strengthened investigative powers\n\nTypical AML laws generally:\n- Require financial institutions to verify customer identities\n- Mandate reporting of large cash transactions\n- Establish compliance programs\n- Create legal frameworks for prosecuting money laundering\n- Impose significant criminal and civil penalties\n\nInternational organizations like the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) also provide global standards and recommendations for combating money laundering.\n\nSpecific requirements and penalties vary by jurisdiction, but most developed countries have comprehensive AML legal frameworks designed to detect and prevent financial crimes.",
